üéØ 8. Key Findings & Conclusions

Encounter Classification

The best classifier was GB (Tuned) with F1 = 0.8892. Tree-based and ensemble methods consistently outperformed linear models. The most important features were procedure count and total procedure cost, confirming that the type of care delivered strongly signals the encounter class.

Mortality Prediction

The best mortality predictor was Gradient Boosting (F1 = 0.8756). Age and total healthcare cost emerged as the strongest predictors. Using balanced class weights was essential due to the low mortality rate.

Cost Prediction

RF Regressor achieved R¬≤ = 0.9685. Procedure cost and duration were the dominant predictors, as expected in a fee-for-service cost model.

Patient Segmentation

K-Means identified 2 distinct patient segments. Clusters differ primarily in healthcare utilisation intensity (total encounters, emergency visits, costs). These segments can support targeted intervention strategies.
